  "prompt": "Is it bad to take Plan B, the morning after pill, multiple times?",
  "response": "Taking Plan B (the morning-after pill) multiple times is generally considered safe in terms of immediate health effects, but it is not recommended as a primary method of contraception. Plan B is designed for occasional use and should not replace regular birth control methods. \n\nUsing Plan B repeatedly can lead to some potential issues:\n\n1. **Menstrual Cycle Disruption**: Taking Plan B may cause changes in your menstrual cycle, leading to irregular periods.\n\n2. **Less Effective**: Plan B may be less effective if taken multiple times in a short period. It is most effective when taken as soon as possible after unprotected sex.\n\n3. **Access to Regular Contraception**: Relying on emergency contraception instead of a regular birth control method is not ideal. It\u2019s important to consult with a healthcare provider to find a more sustainable form of contraception.\n\nIf you find yourself needing emergency contraception frequently, it may be worth discussing long-term birth control options with a healthcare professional.",
